[2]
Date: Wed 24 Oct 2018, 7:10 AM
Source: NJ.com [edited]
https://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2018/10/what_is_adenovirus_virus_causing_severe_outbreak_a.html


New Jersey health officials are continuing to investigate the severe viral outbreak at a New Jersey pediatric center. And while many questions remain, here is what we do know so far about the deadly virus that has killed at least 6 children, as well as [about] the facility where it all occurred.

How many kids have died from the virus outbreak? How many are ill?

The New Jersey Department of Health is investigating 18 cases of adenovirus among pediatric residents at the Wanaque Center for Rehabilitation and Nursing in Haskell, Passaic County, which officials said included "very ill children," some of whom were on ventilators and had trachea tubes. A total of 6 of these cases have resulted in fatalities.

What is adenovirus?

Adenovirus illnesses can mimic symptoms of the flu and common cold. But this group of viruses is something else entirely. Adenoviruses often attack the respiratory tract and tend to affect infants and children, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). Illnesses from the virus are usually mild and people typically recover in a matter of days. But because symptoms can appear so similar to the flu and common cold, it can be tricky to diagnose.
Though less common, in some cases, infections from adenovirus can be potentially life-threatening, particularly those with weakened immune systems.

What kind of facility is the Wanaque Center? Why were children there?

The Wanaque Center is a 227-bed, for-profit facility that serves as an adult nursing home and rehabilitation center for short- and long-term care, and also works with "medically fragile" children. A state health department spokeswoman said they included "very ill children, who are on ventilators and have trachea tubes," who have compromised immune systems and have been at the facility for years.

How does the virus usually spread?

Adenovirus outbreaks often occur when there are many people in close quarters, like at a medical facility. According to the CDC, adenoviruses are usually spread from an infected person to others through:
- Close personal contact (touching or shaking hands).
- Coughing and sneezing.
- Touching an object or surface with adenoviruses on it, then touching your mouth, nose, or eyes before washing your hands.

[Byline: Spencer Kent and Ted Sherman]

