[5] Background to the outbreak
Date: Wed 24 Oct 2018, 7:01 PM
Source: The Washington Post, Associated Press [edited]
https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/the-latest-health-chief-doesnt-see-wider-threat-from-virus/2018/10/24/5d53c376-d7b7-11e8-8384-bcc5492fef49_story.html?utm_term=.06f3c354ab27


The Latest on a fatal viral outbreak in New Jersey (all times local):
---------------------------------------------------------------------
5:40 PM
Health officials say the 1st symptoms associated with the deadly viral outbreak at nursing facility in northern New Jersey showed up on [Wed 26 Sep 2018], 2 weeks before the state was notified of an outbreak.

State health officials were notified [Tue 9 Oct 2018] of the adenovirus infections at the Wanaque Center for Nursing and Rehabilitation.

But state health commissioner Dr. Shereef Elnahal told a news conference [Wed 24 Oct 2018] that it's always difficult to know exactly when an actual outbreak begins.

A total of 7 patients, mostly children, have died this month [October 2018] as a result of being infected with the virus; 11 others are recovering.

The health commissioner says that all the infections occurred in the facility's respiratory, or ventilator unit.

Some pediatric patients at the rehab center have been there most or all of their lives.

4:50 PM
The head of a New Jersey nurses union says staff nurses at a rehab center where a viral outbreak has killed 7 patients complained about staffing shortages, which they say might lead to poor infection control.

Deborah White is president of the Health Professionals and Allied Employees union. She says in a statement that the 70 nurses represented by the union are working to contain the spread of the adenovirus at the Wanaque Center for Nursing and Rehabilitation "under difficult circumstances". She notes what the nurses say are dangerous staffing shortages.

At least 18 pediatric patients at the facility were infected with the adenovirus that as of [Wed 24 Oct 2018] evening had killed 7 people, including many children and at least one young adult.

The facility's 2016 inspection noted a shortage of clinical nursing assistants that ranged from about 6 to 12% of the needed coverage during several days of monitoring in March [2016]. Later inspections did not note the problem.

1:40 PM
New Jersey's health commissioner says it's unlikely a viral outbreak at a pediatric rehabilitation center that left 7 "medically fragile" people dead will pose a wider threat.

Dr. Shereef Elnahal said in an interview with the Associated Press on [Wed 24 Oct 2018] that he doesn't "see a major outbreak risk in the community". He says that's because the adenovirus that infected at least 18 pediatric patients at the Wanaque Center for Nursing and Rehabilitation, in Haskell, commonly results in only mild illnesses among people with healthy immune systems.

The health department says most of those who died were under 18 [years-old]. At least one is a young adult. Health officials had been describing all those infected as children, which is the way the health facility describes its pediatric patients even though it says some are as old as 22 [years].

Federal inspectors over the past few years found isolated violations of rules governing infection control.

9:30 AM
Another child has died following a severe viral outbreak at a New Jersey rehabilitation center for "medically fragile children," bringing the death toll to 7.

There have been 18 cases overall of adenovirus at the Wanaque Center for Nursing and Rehabilitation in Haskell, about 30 mi (approx. 50 km) northwest of New York, the state Health Department said. The 227-bed, for-profit facility cares for children and elderly residents.

The agency had said [Tue 23 Oct 2018] that 6 children had died this month [October 2018]. But the center said it learned [Tue 23 Oct 2018] night that another child had died.

The strain afflicting the children is usually associated with acute respiratory illness, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which on its website instructs health workers to report unusual clusters to state or local health departments.

The Health Department hasn't released the names or the ages of the victims.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[Human adenoviruses (HAdVs) commonly cause infections in children, including epidemic pharyngoconjunctival fever. In adults, HAdVs, particularly types 4 and 7, have caused respiratory infections with considerable morbidity in closed populations, such as in military recruit camps. For some adenovirus serotypes, the clinical spectrum of disease associated with infection varies depending on the site of infection; for example, infection with adenovirus 7 acquired by inhalation is associated with severe lower respiratory tract disease, whereas oral transmission of the virus typically causes no or mild disease [http://www.who.int/water_sanitation_health/bathing/recreadischap6.pdf].

The above reports are indicating a health care facility outbreak due to Adenovirus type 7 [HAdV7] in immunocompromised children with severe disease and fatal outcomes [https://www.jwatch.org/na46465/2018/04/06/severe-adenovirus-type-7-respiratory-infection].

HAdV7 transmission generally occurs through respiratory droplets and close contact, which can lead to rapid and widespread infection. Large community and regional outbreaks of acute respiratory disease with an increased incidence of severe and fatal outcomes caused by HAdV7 have been described in Europe and Asia [1-2]. Nosocomial control of HAdV7 transmission is another challenge faced by health care centers. Thus, control of HAdV7 spread is crucial. However, it is difficult to differentiate pneumonia caused by HAdVs from other types of viral pneumonia, and detection and typing of HAdVs are not routinely performed in hospitals.

There are no approved antiviral treatment options for HAdV infections, and a vaccine against HAdV-7 and HAdV-4 is available only to military personnel. Early efforts to develop a vaccine by growing the virus in monkey tissue culture led to contamination with simian papovavirus (SV-40) and production of a HAdV-SV-40 hybrid virus, fortunately without apparent human pathobiology. Clinicians need to be aware of the possibility of HAdV infection in communal populations and report such outbreaks to local and national public health authorities.

References:
1. Tang L, An J, Yu P and Xu W. Complete genome sequence of human adenovirus type 7 associated with fatal infant pneumonia. Genome Announc. 2013;1(1). pii: e00182-12. doi: 10.1128/genomeA.00182-12. Epub 2013 Feb 14. Available at:
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3569294/.
2. Yamamoto D, Okamoto M, Lupisan S, et al. 2014. Impact of human adenovirus serotype 7 in hospitalized children with severe fatal pneumonia in the Philippines. Jpn J Infect Dis. 2014;67(2):105-10. doi:10.7883/yoken.67.105. Available at:
https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/yoken/67/2/67_105/_pdf/-char/en.
3. Tsou TP, Tan BF, Chang HY, et al. Unknown Pathogen Discovery/Investigation Group. 2012. Community outbreak of adenovirus, Taiwan, 2011. Emerg Infect Dis. 2012;18(11):1825-32. doi: 10.3201/eid1811.120629. Available at:
https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3559173/.
